Proud of all those marching today and making a statement about climate change. Even in my short lifetime it's been startling to see first hand places that used to have snow and glaciers melt out and fade away. To me the high mountains always feel more 'alive' when covered in snow and ice.  A lot of recent trips to the Himalaya have shown the irreversible warming, glaciers are melting out and the even elders know why. While I still fly often for work, I'm choosing to #actonclimate by living in a passive solar home, driving an electric car, cutting out factory farmed meat and dairy from my diet, and doing as much as I can. ~

Photo of me by @cedarwright on our mission to make the first ascent of the SW Cat Ear Spire in Pakistan's Trango Valley, one of the spikey summits in the center of the frame.  @thenorthface

Home life can be stressful. I write emails from dawn to midnight, stumble during conference calls, sweat my way through all the mind-numbing producing that happens between projects and stories. But then this unpredictable creature @taylorfreesolo dances around our kitchen in her sleeping-bag "dress" and reminds me to look out the window. Watch the spring snow fall. Witness the late afternoon light as it stops time for a few seconds.  @thenorthface @chloebartoli @bartolistyle @sonyalpha @parkcitydesignbuild

Echoing the words from @thenorthface in this important time of change - "In our country‚Äôs infancy, our leaders had the brilliance and foresight to protect our nation‚Äôs epic natural lands, not for business, but to feed our souls and create life-long conservationists. Most notably among these was Teddy Roosevelt and his powerful vision to enact the 1906 American Antiquities Act. Consider for a moment a world without the sacred rocks and stone temples of our heritage, or without the great ranges and life-supporting waters, open to all and owned by all, who wish to connect with the natural world. We fundamentally believe our National Monuments, Parks and public lands are vital shared spaces and any attempt to change them threatens our heritage, destroying part of the very core of who we have become as a nation. It also erodes the livelihood of 7.6 million people who are employed in outdoor recreation. We stand with the outdoor industry, our customers and the overwhelming majority of Americans who oppose any legislation that would reduce or devalue our National Monuments, Parks and public lands. Protecting and preserving access to these places is core to our mission to enable all people to explore outdoors." #NeverStopExploring

@freddiewilkinson and Zack Smith eyeing out the descent after the first ascent of the South Face of the Mooses Tooth in @denalinps. Stay tuned for more adventures soon in this vast landscape. @thenorthface @sanctityofspace @bluewaterropes

@chrisburkard photo!! with  @taylorfreesolo @sweatpantsmedia @benweiland @heidarlogi @arcticsurfers @jquinny @timmymissions @hogstine @zellnerdy @ellithor @russell_holliday @auroraarktika and many more!

For Earth Day I wanted to explain how what we witnessed during the @natgeo @thenorthface #TheLastHoneyHunter expedition changed my worldview.  I couldn't quite articulate it so here is the wisdom from @jetbutteflies: ~

In Nepal‚Äôs remote Hongu River valley, the Kulung tribe still practice an ancient and powerful form of animism that is overseen by local shamans. For the Kulung, the entire universe is encapsulated within this isolated watershed. The very first humans descended from the snowy Himalayan peaks to the north almost twenty generations ago. The Kulung know that when they die, their souls will join a growing congress of ancestors that live under the massive rock outcropping to the south. ~

One does not choose to become a shaman. Rather, the spirits come to select individuals during their dreams and possess them. Thus conscripted, the shamans find their sacred tools using their intuition and dreams as guidance. They sew sacred headdresses from porcupine quills and perform healing and religious functions for the communities - often at great physical and psychic cost to themselves. ~

In the west, we struggle to find connection with our own place in the world - to understand our own traditions, dreams and messages from our own ancestors.  Earth Day is a start. We are creating our own rituals and striving for a connection to the soil from which we have all risen, and into which we will all someday return. ~

Also we are proud to announce that the World Premiere for the film will be held at this years @mountainfilm festival in Telluride!! ~

@irving_matthew @sadiequarrier @dzifoundation @ben_knight @taylorfreesolo @m_synnott

A young Kulung Rai boy with a doko basket full of greens making his way out of the forest and back to the village of Saddi, Nepal.  During our @natgeo #TheLastHoneyHunter expedition we saw startling change and modernization with the younger generations in this remote shamanistic community.  But at moments like this we also realized the core of this culture and its traditions are as deeply rooted as it's jungle home. ~

@irving_matthew @sadiequarrier @jetbutterflies

A woman turns a newly-built prayer wheel in the tiny settlement of Ngawal, Manang Valley, Nepal. Like the rapid increase in global communications and connectivity, small roads are expanding across Nepal‚Äôs steep hills at an alarming rate. Before this, amenities like cement or acrylic paint were rare due to the cost and difficulty of transport. ~

Directly across the small town square from the prayer wheel stands an ancient willow tree, upwards of five feet in diameter and a medieval Buddhist chorten. The tree was planted by the first settlers to Ngawal, centuries and countless generations ago. ~

While the exteriors have changed, the fundamentals of village life are so far remaining constant. ~

Words by @jetbutterflies! with @climber.abiral @sodapopchamling @rudy.le @pasang_lhamu_sherpa_akita @yeti @thenorthface @camp4collective @sonyalpha

@thenorthface @mike.gauthier @taylorfreesolo @sonyalpha

Observing the process of hunting in Nepal // words by @nomadic49ak- It's a strange feeling as a guide to travel to a far off land & be the hunter myself this time, rather than let others take care of the animal. I made the initial cuts and then I could tell the guides & porters were eager to begin their work. The Nepali gentlemen made quick work of the sheep. After skinning, a slit was made to remove the stomach & intestines. The intestines were cleaned out, and the stomach was opened to remove all grass being digested inside. At that point I figured we would quarter & split up the loads of meat since there more than enough bodies to help carry out. Instead, the whole carcass - organs, stomach and intestines - were loaded into ONE basket and one porter took off back to camp. That was obviously his job and he took pride in the load of sheep meat. There will be no waste of this old ram. ~

@bennyob301 @irish_goodbye @jetbutterflies @sitkagear @thenorthface @yeti - slow shutter shot on the @sonyalpha a7rii with a @syrp_ ND

Last light on Nepal's Manaslu Himalaya seen from 17,000 ft on the back side of the Annapurna massive.  This is the moment when the long, rough road to basecamp ends and the climbing begins! ~ 
With @jetbutterflies @climber.abiral @rudy.le @camp4collective @freeflysystems @pasang_lhamu_sherpa_akita @sodapopchamling @reddigitalcinema @yeti

@sodapopchamling is a glorious misfit - bending strings and expectations in Nepal. ~

Her Nepali parents traveled as part of the famous British Gurkha Rifles brigade, and Sareena grew up in Hong Kong, Singapore and the UK. Her rebellious streak was fed by the heyday of the punk scene. She taught herself to play guitar - starting by making up her own chords, then graduated to writing songs and starting bands. ~

Upon returning to Nepal, she helped crystalize Nepal‚Äôs vibrant punk and metal music scene - singing original music in Nepali and English that tackled political and social issues, as well as gave young fans a rare chance to let loose and rebel. ~

Anyone who has been thrashed in a mosh pit or sweated through your boots skanking at a ska show understands the poignant liberation tucked into the backbeat of a ska song, in power chords played loud and hard and fast. It‚Äôs a freedom that is often felt most strongly in the hours after the show closes, ears still ringing, soaked in silence and cool air. ~ 
Sareena is like this. She is built of silence more than of noise. At first glance - or first read - one might see only a rebel and a screamer. But, have a conversation with her and instead you see a strong woman pulled by deep dreams of equality and happiness, driven by a real love for her community and her family. Sareena lives her values in a way that few people can claim to. She is a mother of two adopted children. A philosopher. A climber. A teacher. She, quite literally, rocks. ~

Words by @jetbutterflies!! w @climber.abiral @pasang_lhamu_sherpa_akita @rudy.le @yeti #nepaliloveyou #punk

@pasang_lhamu_sherpa_akita is one of the busiest women in Nepal. ~

The week before this photo was taken, she was on a flight back from New York City where she received the prestigious Tenzing Norgay award from the Explorer‚Äôs Club. In less than a week since, she has attempted to put up a new route on an unclimbed peak in the Annapurna region and left to join her teammates on the first Nepali Women‚Äôs Expedition to climb Mt. Kanchenjunga (28,333 ft) - the third tallest mountain on the planet. ~

She is Nepal‚Äôs leading female mountain guide, and has received international attention for her groundbreaking ascents of Mt. Everest and K2, as well as her work helping remote communities rebuild after the devastating 2015 earthquakes in Nepal. ~

Pasang grew up in the fabled Khumbu valley that leads up to the slopes of Mt Everest. She lost her parents at a young age, and raised her younger sister as she pursued a career in the mountains. Often the only woman climbing, Pasang struggled to break through in an industry (and society) with a very limited vision of what women can, or should, do. ~

But this is steadily changing, thanks to pioneering individuals including Pasang. She has become a national hero without losing her kindness and connection to her family and her community. Her example has inspired a generation of young women to climb and to strive for more than what society demands.  And this is just the beginning. ~

Words by @jetbutterflies @sodapopchamling @climber.abiral  @rudy.le @yeti @camp4collective 
#nepaliloveyou #mountainninja #sherpa

Expedition update // words by @jetbutterflies // Annapurna III and Nilgiri backlit by lightning from our acclimatization camp in a sea of scree above the small village of Ngawal, 16,000 feet. ~

A few hours outside of Kathmandu, the main highway crosses the Marshyangdi river. Here, the river is cut into a steep valley and tumbles violently between massive boulders, angry and deep. If you turn right and follow the river upstream, it undulates through cliffs and canyons, past small villages with men and oxen pacing across thimble-sized terraces on the steep slopes of the valley. The river calms as you gain elevation, shifting from blue to azure. ~

This magical valley sneaks around the Himalayas themselves and into the dusty rain shadow between the fertile mid-hills of Nepal and the high-altitude desert of Tibet. There are few places on earth where you can experience so much vertical relief in all directions. This geography creates a certain silence, a gravity that is nearly impossible to describe. It leaves you feeling tiny. Quiet. Humble. Nauseous from the thin air, from the realization of our own insignificance. ~  @sodapopchamling @pasang_lhamu_sherpa_akita @climber.abiral  @rudy.le @royalenfield @yeti @irish_goodbye @thenorthface @reddigitalcinema @sonyalpha

What's YOUR nerdy secret? Thanks to everyone who came out to our First Fridays party this past weekend! We had a blast celebrating the launch of Creators Media with these nerdy confessionals.

IT'S MY 29th BIRTHDAY! And it's the reason why I need a break from Social Media.

___

For the past 10 years, I have exposed my entire life to Social Media. Everyone knew what I loved to do, what I loved to eat, my family outings, my friends, my work. I have given the internet my ALL.

___

I have been applauded for my work, and I have also been scrutinized for it. I have been loved, I have been hated. I was honest, but I was also no fool to the fact that Social Media was an addiction.

___

I decided to take a break from Social Media to reconnect with myself. Nothing major has happened, and I am well. I just have to do this for me.

___

Thank you for the birthday wishes. I'll see you soon.

___

She kneeled down to tie her shoe-laces, dressed in complete black, just like the other participants. "Scared?", a guy asked her, staring down at her. As she picked up her paintball gun, her response was ready, until her eyes met his. "Loser buys the other a pretzel at Dawn", she smiled, putting her head gear on. "I'll look forward to having you buy me one", he smiled, and put on his head gear. The clock had struck midnight at @WaltDisneyWorld, and everyone began running in different directions. Winner gets a years VIP pass at the park, and this year was hers. The hundreds of people scattered across the park, as she kneeled behind one of the Disney castles bushes. The sound of Mickey's battle horn was heard, she closed her eyes. And ran. 
___

Hours into the night, the numbers of participants dwindled, as the total number left was displayed on the castle in the middle of the Park. "Three", she whispered, her heart beating fast. All of a sudden she heard a paintball shot from behind her, and saw that 'he' shot someone who was about to shoot her. "Saved you", he shouted from afar. The number '2' indicated that they were the only ones left. "Now what?", he yelled. She aimed the paintball gun at him, and so did he at her. "THREE", she yelled. He realized what she was doing, and so he yelled back, "TWO". She closed her eyes, "ONE". And the shots were fired at the both of them. They both won that night, as it was a tie, but more importantly, they both bought the other a pretzel. End scene.

___

He saw her from the distance, dressed in his finest uniform with the royal emblem on his right. "You came", he whispered behind her. His father, the King, stared down at them both. She turned around, in her canary gown, and bowed immediately. "Your highness", she said, tilting her head slightly. "Dance with me", he kneeled down to grab her hands and slowly got up with her. The King eyed the two of them, displeased with her. "I'm sorry", she turned to walk away. "You must remember", he begged her, taking a step forward. "I told you, I can't, I don't know you", she said, walking away. He quickly realized this may be the last time he saw her, and so he quickly went around her. "Dance with me", he let out his hand and bowed, "Please". She quickly took his hand, out of shock that a prince would bow to her. "Alright", she whispered.

___

The violins began, and his hand slid around her waist. One foot after the other, and on the ballroom floor they danced. She looked him in the eye, as the slowly spun, and her heart fluttered. His legs leading hers, as he twirled her once, her stomach had butterflies. Their pace got quicker, as all of his guests left the dance floor to look at them. It was a sight of pure chemistry, movement in its finest. As he dipped her, and picked her up again, her head rested on his shoulder. His smell was intense, and in that instant, it all came rushing back. "I remember", she said with a smile, and so did he. Her smile quickly faded when she remembered who tried to hurt her, and what caused her amnesia. One look at him, and he knew she remembered. The King. End scene.

___

I grew up faster than I would have liked to. All I've ever known was to be the responsible one. Nobody knows the real wars we face, nobody needs to. I'd be the one that would work 100% just so that a loved one wouldn't have to. If I love you, I'll fight your battles for you. If it's something you need, I'll give you mine. The world is a scary place, so let me protect you. I'm messed up, but from afar I'm a chaotic masterpiece. I know some of you relate. The world thinks I'm pushing against that wall because I'm afraid of letting the demons in, when in fact I'm pushing it to save them from my demons coming out.

___

You can't keep your loved ones together if you're caught falling apart. Get those wounded fists up, it's round two.

___

She sat in her gown, bored out of her mind. Her family held an annual party for the Elite families of America at the Hamptons every year. She felt she was being strangled by the dress, this wasn't her. A boy caught her eye, to which he bowed his head as he raised his glass. She rolled her eyes, that was it. A moment later she snuck behind the stage and plugged in her iPhone, and changed the tracks. He saw what she did, and smirked. She was in the middle of the dance floor, her parents in shock. Girls left their partners in the middle of their Waltz, and began grabbing drinks and danced with her. Parents across the courtyard began whispering, as her father felt the most ashamed.

___

She felt the music pass through her, as more of her generation joined her on the dance floor. All of a sudden, the music had stopped. Her father approached her, "This isn't who your supposed be", he said. Her eyes connected with the handsome boy that smiled at her before, as he ran past her and her father, and jumped off the dock and into the water. "That's because you never took time to know me," she said, taking off her shoes. As if in slow motion, she turned around, and RAN. Her generation behind her, as they rushed passed the dance floor, on to the deck, as the sun kissed the horizon, and JUMPED. Her eyes, met his. They were free. End scene.

___

She walked into the Galleria Vittorio Emanuele II, with her clutch in hand. Her Chanel suit, with glasses to match, you could hear her heels from the echo of the glass and iron roof. On the corner of her left, she saw one. On her right, another two. She noticed the entire space was emptier than usual, and she saw people being evacuated from the other side. She reached the middle, and dropped her clutch. As she bent to pick it up, the three men approached her from behind. Kicking one from the back, as she grabbed another's arm, held his gun, and knocked the other with his elbow. "STOP", she heard from behind. As she stood above the three unconscious agents, she turned to face 'him'. Their eyes connected.

___

Silence as for the next sixty seconds, it was just the two of them. Their guns pointing at each-other. "Don't do this", he whispered. She could hear the sirens, and her eyes began to tear. All she remembered was Cuba, with him. "Put the gun down", he said. She slowly raised her gun towards the sky, and he sighed. The next moment, she fired the gun. He covered his head, as the pieces of glass fell. He then looked up, and so her being lifted by a rope to a helicopter. He aimed his gun at her, but couldn't do it. As she got away, he caught a note that she dropped. She may have gotten away from the law, but she was still his. All the letter said was, 'Cuba'. He booked his flight. End scene.

Have you ever lost a good friend and wondered why? Thinking back to see whether it was something either of you did wrong. There are people I pushed away, but some I admittedly let go. Sometimes I get these moments where flashes of memories come back, and I remember the good times. I wish them well, until this very day. But it makes me think. There was a point when those people came into our lives where we didn't see an end coming so soon. And now my question comes to you guys. If you knew someone in your life had an expiration date on your friendship, would you still be their friend? Would you still invest your time? Knowing that you will make amazing memories in the present, but they won't be a part of your future. Don't forget, with good memories also comes bad ones. Thoughts.

He parked his carriage outside the chapel, and waited for the newlyweds to come out. As he saw the cameras getting ready, he made sure everything about the carriage was perfect. They came out with a reception of applause and flashes of lights. The bride got on the carriage and tossed the bouquet, with girls jumping to catch it. He signaled his horse, and the carriage made its way. Under the tall trees of Central Park, he smiled as he saw the couple in eachother's embrace. He knew a special route under the cherry blossom trees that was magical. He wanted them to have a beginning worth remembering. His job was simple, but he took it to heart. A marriage was the start to a journey, and he was the start of it.

___

As the afternoon came, he took his now-empty carriage down his usual path. He pulled slightly so the horse knew to stop. Entering the cemetery, his path made his way to her gravestone. Kneeling down with a small bouquet of roses, he said a little prayer. She had passed away the week before their marriage, and he had never married since. Now that years have passed, he has found some peace in the fact that it was meant to be. While they never had a beginning, he could at least ensure someone else has one they'd remember forever. End scene.

___

She watched the raindrops fall down her window, as she could hear her parents argument through the walls. She saw a small pebble thrown at her window, and saw 'him' standing down in their courtyard. Her frown disappeared, as she looked back at her door, and then lifted her window to escape down the vines. He saw the look in her eyes, and the sadness. Holding her hand, he pulled her to his motorbike and drove off. She felt the wind on her face, as her arms wrapped tightly around his waist, her face rested on his back. They drove down the coast, and the blue ocean and golden beaches called to them, as the clouds had suddenly faded and the sun came out. She splashed him, to which he splashed her back.

___

They drove downtown and noticed the road was blocked. He smiled and entered the marathon with his bike; and noticed it was a color run. The splashes of color being thrown at them. The entire street burst in splashes of color, as tears of joy fell down her face. Drinks were handed out to them, and she shared hers with him. Watching him take a sip, she smiled. Her heart fluttered. In her world of black and white, she made him see in color. End scene.

___

He opened the doors of the @LexingtonBrass, as his 8 year old son followed amazed by the interior. They stood behind a couple in line for their table, and his son kept himself occupied by admiring the wallpaper. The couple in front of them noticed this odd behavior, and gave a confused look when they saw the kid so focused on it. They were then seated, and it was their turn next. He grabbed his sons hand, "Our tables ready bud", he smiled. His son looked at his father with tears in his eyes, and grabbed his hand back. They were seated at a table near the couple they were standing behind at the entrance line. They looked at the little boy, as his eyes lit up when he saw coloring paper and crayons on the restaurants table.

___

As they waited for their food to arrive, he watched his son try to color. The little boy took a good three minutes to stare at each color, and then used it. The couple noticed that he wasn't coloring, but instead using each color and simply stroking lines. "Hi, we didn't want to interrupt", the couple said in pity, "but maybe you should see someone about your son". The father smiled, and turned to whisper to them. "My son just had a procedure done," he looked back at his son, "He can now see for the first time in his life". Their food arrived, and as the couple backed up in shame, he smiled at his son who's eyes lit up when he saw the colorful food in front of him. Never judge a book by its cover, or a person by your assumption. End scene.

___

He walked her to the door of her house, she smiled at him, as he leaned in for a kiss. After doing so, she realized she was falling for him. "I need to show you something", she said, walking him inside. They sat opposite each-other on the living room floor, as she got closer and held his hand. "You know I care about you", her eyes on the floor, "a lot actually". He grabbed her hands, "I care about you a lot too", he replied, smiling. "But there's something you need to know about me", she said, her eyes slowly focused on his, she was afraid he'd think she was weird. In that moment all he could focus on was her eyes, and her eyes alone. He realized that he had already fallen for her. "I need you to close your eyes", she whispered. "Alright", he whispered.

___

Her heart was beating faster than ever before, "Open them", she whispered. As he did, he noticed they were both floating off the ground slightly. He didn't panic, and instead looked at her and smiled. As they slowly touched the floor again, he didn't say anything and got up and walked away. Her heart sank, until she saw him coming back with a book from her shelf. "I need you to close your eyes", he whispered. He took her hand and placed it on the book with his. "Open them", he whispered. As she did, the book opened, and out came hundreds of butterflies. Her eyes teared up as they filled the house. She wasn't alone. He may be weird, but he was her kind of weird. End scene.

It's ironic that I'm posting this picture right now. I've been talking to a close friend about the future, and how I wish we 'knew'. You know? Obviously it's something we've all thought about. Knowing what the future may hold. Some of us are eager to find out exactly what, while others would rather not know. I envy the people who don't have the need to find out. You could see it in their care-free nature and euphoric soul. I often ask myself about the future before I even start anything. Does that make sense? I'd be the type that would sabotage things just because I see no future in it. Emphasis on "I see", and the fact that I'm completely putting a conclusion based on an assumption.

___

If only there was a crystal ball that we could look into that would be able to tell us where we're headed. Or how much we have to push in order to get to that goal? Is there a finish line? I'm caught up in all of these questions. I wanted to know what you think? Would you rather know your future, or not? Any advice for someone who's looking for answers? Waiting for your thoughts.

Merry Christmas‚Ä¶.. meet the kinkajou (Potos flavus), the king of the tree crown in Central America. At night, kinkajous are the dominant animals in the Balsa tree (Ochroma pyramidale) and chase everybody out of the canopy so they can have the nectar to themselves - each flower can hold up to 50 ml of sugary nectar. Kinkajous are very important pollinators and seed dispersers of many species of rain forest trees, and they are the primary pollinator of the Ochroma tree pictured here. The kinkajous visit to drink nectar from the huge flowers and while drinking their furry cheeks get dusted in pollen that they carry to the next flower. This picture was taken from atop of a 100 ft tower to access the forest canopy in central Panama. @thephotosociety @natgeocreative #Panama #conservation

I found this beautiful skull lying on a beach on Jicaron Island (a small island to the south of Coiba), its probably from a little whale or a dolphin. Coiba is Central America‚Äôs largest uninhabited island (some 500 square kilometers) and sits just off the Pacific coast of Panama. It is a truly unique place with many endemic species of animals and plants. It was a penal colony for almost 100 years until 10 years ago, and so it is still covered with lush rainforest that has long gone on the mainland - a time capsule with high conservation value. Together with my colleague @timlaman (under water), @peter_houlihan and @pelletk (video). We are working on a celebrational photo essay about Coiba National Park.

Our expeditions (three so far) are supported by the International League of Conservation Photographers (@ilcp_photographers), el Ministerio de Ambiente Panama @miambientepma and STRI (stri.si.edu). Fusing scientific exploration and photography to support Coiba‚Äôs #conservation. GEO magazine published 2 articles about Coiba‚Äôs fantastic ecosystem in July and August 2016. #nanpapix #Coiba

I enjoyed photographing this male very much, he was so relaxed just sitting in a tree ‚Äì he seemed to be thinking about something. @thephotosociety @natgeo @natgeocreative #Wpph14 #conservation #ecology #DRC #congo #bonobo

Photograph taken by @christianziegler in DRC on assignment for @natgeo, an outtake from a story on Bonobos in March 2013. After tracking the Bonobos for many weeks they became accustomed to me and sometimes the group would just hangout together - relaxing, stretching and grooming.  This bonobo was lying on its back stretching out his arms. @thephotosociety @natgeo @natgeocreative #Wpph14 #conservation #ecology #DRC #congo #bonobo

Photograph taken by @christianziegler in DRC on assignment for @natgeo, from a story on Bonobos in March 2013. This is a very young Bonobo, maybe less than 3 months old, with her mother. i took this picture to give an impression of the scale of #v√∂lklingen ironworks and it's my last one too.
#worldheritage #industrialarchitecture

as mentioned in a previous post, the #v√∂lklingen ironworks is also showplace of the #urbanartbiennale2017.
more than 100 street artists from all over the world exhibit their work on over 100,000 square meters within the raw space of the industrial heritage. definitely an interesting environment for art in general and a second reason to visit this location.
#thespacesilike #worldheritage #urbanart (as shown by @artofdavidwalker)
inside the beast - #v√∂lklingen #worldheritage
o like orange juice - #v√∂lklingen #roundseries w/ @vomstreunern

today we went to see this rusty industrial beauty, that kinda looks like mordor, located in the town of #v√∂lklingen (south-west germany).
back in the days it used to be a place for ironworks and was closed more than 30 years ago.
in 1994 the abandoned v√∂lklingen ironworks was declared as world heritage site by the @unesco.
i have to say, that the scale of this place is absolutely overwhelming and it breathes history in every corner, thanks to its perfect preservation.
right now, a few parts of the site are home of the #urbanartbiennale2017, which made it even more interesting to visit.

The new AMG S63 S 4MATIC+ "The Luxury Rocket Launcher".
New peak of performance: M177 4.0L V8 biturbo engine with twin-scroll turbochargers

The versatile AMG 4.0L biturbo V8 engine in the S 63 S 4MATIC+ takes peak performance to a new level at 450kW (612hp). Maximum torque attains a new best value of 900Nm. It is available over a broad engine speed range of 2750 to 4500rpm and so provides a feeling of effortless superiority in every accelerator pedal position. A sprint from zero to 100 km/h is absolved in 3.5 seconds, and this dynamic acceleration only ends at the governed top speed of 250km/h (with AMG Driver's package: 300km/h).
The advanced AMG 4.0L V8 biturbo engine utilises well-proven twin turbocharging, with the two chargers not located outside on the cylinder banks, but rather between them in the V of the cylinders. The advantages of the "hot inner V" are a compact engine design, an immediate response from the twin-scroll turbochargers and low exhaust gas emissions thanks to optimum air flow for the close-coupled catalytic converters. 
Two twin-scroll turbochargers are deployed for the first time to boost performance and improve responsiveness further. The housing is divided into two parallel flow passages. Combined with two separate exhaust ducts in the exhaust manifold, this makes it possible to control the exhaust gases on the turbine wheel separately. The exhaust gas from the first and fourth cylinders of the cylinder bank is fed into one duct and exhaust gas from the second and third cylinders to the other duct. The aim is to prevent the individual cylinders from having mutually adverse effects on the gas cycle.
The results are increased output due to improved cylinder charge with fresh mixture, more torque at low revs and very immediate response times.

we spend our nights restless because we spend our days on people who ruin our peace and so we lay in bed, over thinking about people who rarely think about us. we spend our days too distracted with social media, we've ruined opportunities to be social. we'd rather watch others live life, double tapping, giving likes to others, those who were brave enough to deviate from a lifestyle that we claim to hate. searching for something in others that we can simply give ourselves but we'd rather not look within and so we live this life looking to people who will disappoint us but we'll accept it because it's familiar, we're unfamiliar with true happiness and we fear things we're not familiar with, so it's good, we walk away and if it's too good, we run away. we're all claiming to be different and yet we're doing the same things. we're all claiming to want more and yet we've settled for less and you're just restless. thinking about things and or people who will never think of you, the way you think of them but hey, you're only human and wanting more or walking away from less is easier said than done and so you'll just take your time, no...you'll waste your time because you think you have time but life is too short. #rhsin #bookstagram

#NudeYogaGirlAlphabet E= Enthusiasm, eBooks and Energy.
‚ù§Ô∏è
In the alphabet of my life E would be Enthusiasm. That's the almost best feeling that I know. I want to be a person who is enthusiastic because that affects others and I think it's a big power of life. I'm happy that I've found many things which make me enthusiastic and that I can follow a path and dreams which make me excited about the future!
‚ù§Ô∏è
E would be also eBooks. I found them just about a year ago, but nowadays I like to listen books when I clean up or do other homework. Also when I'm travelling. Mainly I listen different biographies and nonfiction books.
‚ù§ 
And E would be Energy. That's the biggest motivation to me for a healthy lifestyle and eat well. I want to have energy to chase my dreams and do things which make me happy. ‚ù§
"She wore a thousand faces all to hide her own." ‚ù§

Someone who is struggling with overweight asked me a few days ago assuming... "It takes a lot of work to stay in the condition that you are, right?" I was thinking right away, no! üòä
‚ù§Ô∏è
I'm not in any fitness condition at all or even in fashion model measures anymore (and it doesn¬¥t bother me, I wouldn't be willing to sacrifice what it requires) but I'm feeling that I'm in the best condition of my life. I may not be just today, but generally in the last 2 years. I'm feeling good, I sleep well, my metabolism works, I'm not stressed by weight, my weight stays about the same, even though I haven't been weighing myself for years or restricting my eating almost at all. I'm happy with myself and I can enjoy the food and the life I love.
‚ù§Ô∏è
Of course, all of those go hand by hand, but the point is that I've put the least effort in staying in shape during the last couple of years. I haven't performed health at all, I haven't been hungry, I haven't felt bad because of anything I've eaten, I haven't forced myself to train if I'm tired.
‚ù§Ô∏è
When you find balance, treasure it. It took many years for me to find it, because I tried all different kinds of strict diets. They mixed my metabolism and hormone functions. If you eat too long too little and irregularly, it can slow down your metabolism. And I've been in that vicious circle. I can't recommend it. So forget diets and choose a permanently healthy and flexible lifestyle! ‚ù§Ô∏èüòò

Sometimes the smallest step in the right direction ends up being the biggest step of your life.‚ù§

I'm used to live in uncertainty. I think many of us do because of different reasons: money situations, diseases, temporary work, no work... I mainly because of places where I'm living/working and traveling. For¬†the last ten years I've lived month by month almost all the time - many times day by day too. People may think how exciting when your future is so open, when anything can happen. Yes, I like it mostly too and it was my choice.
‚ù§ 
But I can tell it's also annoying and worrying sometimes because you never know where you're going to be and it's hard to plan anything with others. It's also always packing, actually many times I'm unpacking and packing again at the same time. And it's not easy to make a home and routines and friends when you don't spend enough time for that.
‚ù§ 
I try to enjoy situations and mostly I think "It's not like this for an eternity." I guess?! But today I got reminded that sometimes I just have to make decisions, like in the morning when I booked flight tickets for this weekend. I thought about this already for weeks: Where I'm going and when, for how long I'm going to stay etc.. This takes a lot of energy and time especially because I change my mind all the time.
‚ù§ 
Making decisions is a good skill. I think things happen when the time is right and we can trust also the unknow. But I can't be passive. Usually I listen to my intuition and trust what it says. But sometimes it says nothing, like today. I don't know if I made a good decision but I think the main thing was to make one. Now I feel good because I don't have to think anymore about what to do. Maybe we just have to make decisions even if we aren't 100% sure?!
‚ù§Ô∏è
One question once a week... How old are you? ‚ù§ I'm 27.üòä I would like to know you better.‚ù§

What skills do I want to improve? Today I've thought about that and what I can do more... It feels so good when hard work pays off. I don't want to go the easiest way in life, I want to learn all the time. So here are my 3 most important skills which I'm going to improve at.
‚ù§ 
1. English. Absolutely! There are still lot of things to do to get my English more fluent. (keeping my account has improved my writing skills a lot.) I also want to learn one more language so I want to improve and get more courage to speak different languages.
‚ù§ 
2. Yoga and meditation. You can't really get ready with them... And I want to improve my skills with these two through my whole life with! For example I want to get better in bringing deep breaths and presence to my everyday life I want also to get better at all arm balance asanas.
‚ù§ 
3. Photographing and especially finding my own strong style. Of course, I feel that I own a style already and have found it but as an artist I always question it. I doubt my choiches and try different things because there are so many ways to do photos. I want to improve my eye, skills and view endlessly. I still think I'm in the beginning even if I trust myself more than ever when photographing.
‚ù§ 
What skills do you want to improve?üòä

#NudeYogaGirlAlphabet D= Dream, Different, Dance and Dessert.‚ù§ In the alphabet of my life D would be Dream. One of my mottos has been for years "If you can dream it, you can do it." And I think dreaming is very important. I hope all of you have a dream or dreams.

I think I've never told you my story, how I ended up here‚Ä¶ So today I want to tell you something about my studying. How school isn't the only way. Passion, believing in yourself and hard work can take you there. This is my life, not anyone elses, I remember thinking when I made the decision that wasn't the most usual when I was 22 years old...
‚ù§Ô∏è
I have noticed that many people nowadays are very lost about what they want to be and who they are. I was there, that's also very ok. There are so many choices, but also so many expectations. I was so lost about what I wanted to do for my profession and what to study... that it made me almost sick. I felt that I'm not good enough in anything, not one particular thing where I would be extra talented or extra interested in. But I knew that inside me there is a lot of energy if I just find the correct way to channel it.
‚ù§Ô∏è
You may be surprised that I have never studied anything that I directly need for my work nowadays. Not photographing, not nutrition, holistic wellbeing, fashion or writing. Not teaching yoga, not marketing or anything else commercial‚Ä¶ At least not at school or courses. By myself, yes. A lot, very much by myself.
‚ù§Ô∏è
What have I studied then? I'm 27, so yes I have been in university and other schools. I've studied the following three: industrial designing, philosophy and sociology. Actually I have always been ‚Äùthe school girl‚Äù. The one who got excellent grades, and who thought studying is very important. It is, I still think that. But you can study things by yourself. Being curious and interested in learning is the most important thing. I liked my studies but they weren't my thing.
‚ù§Ô∏è
I'm happy that I had a courage to stop and left a lot of hard work behind (which of course wasn't for nothing) and followed my heart. Because I've been living my dream and working with my passion for several years now. It was just a different path. And yes, many doubted me for sure. But when I realized this thought, it changed my life forever:  You can be anything!‚ù§ So I want to say this to you: Really, don't let your past determine your future. You can be what you want, what makes you happy!

Not everyday is bright, full of sunshine and cloudless. To be honest those days are boring. Bring on the storms

It seems to come up often in comments on my post, "social media is ruining the outdoors, causing careless people to go to beautiful places and trash them" and that I should stop sharing locations with people. I think about this often. Nearly every time I make a post. I think that there are strong arguments on both sides so I try and find a middle ground but I will move towards one side or the other depending on where the battle is at inside my thoughts. What do you think? Where do you stand? What personal experiences do you have with either side of the argument?
Either way, I want to pled with everyone to go on a hike this week with the specific purpose to pick up garbage on our trails and in our parks. Although social media might be negatively impacting our wild places I would ask you to please be a positive impact. Set a date now and do it please. 
One personal cleaning up garbage can right the wrongs of many careless people and perhaps influence others to make positive changes in how they take care of our wild places #EarthWeek #LeaveNoTrace

This world is beautiful and we need to do our part to take care of it. I challenge everyone while out on your next backpacking trip, road trip, day hike, or walk in the park to take a trash bag with you and pick up garbage that other have carelessly left behind and dispose of it properly. We all need to do our part. Leave no trace not matter who made the mess. Thank you everyone for doing your part. Take a picture of the bag of garbage that you collected while out and send it to me. Make a story on IG and share your efforts with your friends. Let's stop complaining and do something about it.
Photo: Taken while packracking (@alpacka_raft) down a river in Chiapas Mexico with @roundtheworldgirl @jeffreymichaelcarlson @backcountry13.

Last year this is how we spent our anniversary. Alone packrafting down the Escalante River of UT. This year we plan to spend it with the our little girl on her first camping trip. She should be about 1 month old by then and I'm so excited to get to introduce her to the outdoors and travel. If you are interested in following that side of my adventures, feel free to follow me at @moonmountainlife. There isn't really any content there at the moment but that is where I'll be posting about our journey of introducing my little girl once she is born to the natural world and the challenges and successes that we encounter along the way. I will be also posting some behind the scenes content on their. Hope to see some of you over there. 
Lastly be sure to follow my wife @rebornbyadventure for her side of the story as it will be probably more insightful.

In a world with so much visual and textual information at our finger tips it is refreshing to find places that are unknown. Places that are so far off the grid that there aren't photographs, there aren't blogs, and there arent other people around except for maybe a few locals that are minimally, if at all, connected with the rest of the world. #thisispackrafting

Mind blown üò≥ I had seen this waterfall several times on IG before so when I saw the waterfall in person for the first time a few days ago, there were few surprises and thus it didnt impact me strongly (one of the sad effects of looking at so many photos of beautiful places on social media) BUT the amazing part of the experience that blew me away way was while testing out Olympus's OM-D E-M1 Mark II I experienced first hand this cameras incredible image stabilization. I took this photo causally with a 1 second exposure standing on a slippery rock and it turned out tac sharp. That is unreal. So not only is the camera light but now I don't need a tripod unless I'm doing Long exposures of 15 second or more (people report being able to do 15 second exposures hand held) 
Any ways just some techy stuff I learned this weekend while testing the camera out with @getolympus while #capturingWhistler. Most probably don't care about camera stuff so I apologize. This will be my last post about that but some of us, including myself find this ground breaking.

Over the weekend, I joined @getolympus  in Whistler, BC to check out their OM-D E-M Mark II micro 4/3rd camera. In all honesty I was blown away by this camera and I barely scratched the surface as to what the camera could do but over the short time that I spent with this camera my favorite features was #1 the weatherproofing and ruggedness of this camera. We spent 3/4 days in rain, waterfall spray, snowmobiling and skiing and I didn't hide the camera from the elements once and it didn't so much as hiccup. #2 the Image stabilization was insane! Between the electronic stabilization, lens stabilization and camera sensor stabilization, I was casually shooting at 1 second exposures and objected that didn't move were tac sharp. This feature blew my mind. (Ultimate Waterfall/PNW camera?)
Photo: taken with the OM-D E-M Mark II and the 300mm lens (equal to a 600mm on full frame) of Black Tusk Peak near Whistler #capturingwhistler

In a matter of days now, I will be welcoming into this world my daughter Zoey. I'm a complete mess of emotions, ranging from excited to terrified, competent to incompetent, optimistic to pessimistic. I find myself saying to Natasha often, "what are we doing? Are really going to do this? Can I give her everything that she needs? " all while starring at my wife's overly sized pregnant belly and feeling our little girl moving against my hand as if we had a choice in the matter now.
The only emotion that does not waiver, and continues to grow, is my love for this little human being. At times it is overwhelming. I want the best for her. I want to see her happy and successful in whatever she pursues. I want to be the best dad I can be. I want to keep her safe. I want to be able to provide for her and my wife after having quit my job as a nurse and venturing into photography full time without formal education and a blind mans knowledge of what I am doing. 
I just keep reminding myself that the entire human race and life itself exist because every parent has been in similar shoes and must of succeeded. There are cracks in this mentality and negative stories that I'm sure could be shared but this is the hope that I'm clinging on to I reach the end and beginning of a life, as I reach parenthood. #new parent #babymoon
Pictured: Is my wife, @rebornbyadventure, starring up at a unique bend in the river in Johnston Canyon located in Banff NP, Alberta. It was one of the last long road trips that I was able to enjoy with her.

The very first time I saw a picture of Mt. Hood, it was actually of this rock; Illumination Rock. After seeing that photo I found out it was on Mt Hood and I knew I had to go there to see this ice encrusted monolith. Now I can check this off my list of places that I had to see in person üòÅ‚úÖ We left our skis at this spot early in morning to make our climb to the summit via the Reid Headwall more enjoyable. Afterwards we returned to our skis to ski down (pictured). @traveloregon @hoodgorge

Today I traded the thick rim ice covering of Mt. Hood for the thick green moss covering of the Columbia River Gorge. So crazy to experience such wild polar opposites within a few miles of each other all here in Oregon.  Today I hiked the Eagle Creek Trail to Tunnel Falls (my personal favorite hike in the Gorge) due to the length of the hike (12 miles round trip), the pristine forest, beautiful waterfalls, and fewer crowds then you will find in most area along the Gorge, all culminating at Tunnels Falls that has a unique part of the trail that goes through a tunnel behind the Falls.  I can't recommend this hike enough. If you ever visit the Gorge, tick this one off the list and please pack out all of your garbage including the garbage that others leave whether on purpose or accident. #leavenotrace @traveloregon @hoodgorge
Pictured üôã‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è: @misguidedoutfitters. I snapped this photo of him while he and a group he was guiding was hiking by.

Packrafting down through the  Mexican jungle canyon was a surreal experience for me. The most distinct memory that I have of this section was looking straight up out of the narrow canyon and seeing the top of the jungle canopy on both sides growing straight out of the vertical canyon walls. It felt like that moment in the movie "Inception" when the city is bend on itself with city above and below but in this situation it was a jungle with parrots flying from one side to the other. #alpackaraft

Our journey to reach El Arco Del Tiempo (The Arch of Time) via the River was long and involved. We suffered through near death from diarrhea and vomiting, my drone when down in a river due to some weird malfunction, 2 parking tickets, only 2 of the 5 cameras that we had on the trip were still working by the time we reached the El Arco, we spent half a day trying to find some simple gas for our camping stoves, and we were swindled out of money trying to find someone to help us exit the canyon that ultimately delayed our plans to make El Arco. In the moment all of these things were very discouraging but in the end they gave the trip a complex beautiful character that made the trip one of the best I've had in all of my life. 
Now sitting here waiting to take my flight home, I'd simple write this all off as a dream if it weren't for the thousands of photos and hours of video that I have to drool over that I know will inspire me to return again sometime later in my life. Im so grateful for the time and ability that I had to visit this place, for the amazing people that joined me on this trip and that I get to share some of my content with all of you. 
Mad shout out to @alpacka_raft for making the most durable, bad ass packrafts in the world. We beat the crap out of our boats against sharp limestone rocks while going down powerful shallow rapids. They all survived the brutal punishment and were the key to making this trip possible, To @goodtogofoods for providing us with food that not only is the best prepackaged backpacking food in the industry (my opinion) but more importantly keep us healthy and didn't give us diarrhea, and to @keen for making the Newport shoe that kept me going every step of the way. 
Thank you @backcountry13  @roundtheworldgirl @jeffreymichaelcarlson for joining me on this crazy adventure

Blue-and-Yellow Macaw, One of the most recognizable of the #Macaw, this bird is popular as a pet throughout the world thanks to their ability to talk and bond with humans. wild populations are found in South America and ranging as far north as #Florida. The Blue-and-yellow Macaw is not a light bird so the primary feathers have to be long and strong in order for the bird to be capable of sustaining flight. The Macaw's flight feathers are shaped with a shorter leading edge and a longer trailing edge. The leading edge is curved and forces air  over the upper surface of the #wing creating lift during flight.

The Walls of #ChanChan which was believed to have been constructed around 850 AD by the Chim√∫. It was the empire capital city with an estimated population of 40,000-60,000 people.

After the Inca conquered the #Chim√∫ around 1470 AD, Chan Chan fell into decline. In 1535 AD, Francisco #Pizarro founded the Spanish city of #Trujillo which pushed Chan Chan further into the shadows. While no longer the capital city, Chan Chan was still well known for its riches and was looted by the Spaniards. A sixteenth century indication list of items looted from a burial tomb in Chan Chan; a treasure equivalent to 80,000 pesos of gold was recovered (nearly $5,000,000 US dollars)

Chan Chan is in a particularly arid section of the coastal desert of northern Peru. Due to the lack of rain in this area, the major source of water for Chan Chan is in the form of rivers carrying surface runoff from the #Andes. They are dated to the 5th and 6th centuries. The location was chosen carefully and in order to make them majestic. 
As the legends go, by the burning of the dead king and his armour, he was moved to Valhalla (heaven)  by the consuming force of the fire. The fire could reach temperatures of 1500 ¬∞C. Happy to be able to share a photo and the story of my beautiful mother, Paula Schulte, during last night's discussion on Gender at National Geographic @natgeo. My late mother, who was a prolific painter, was a fiercely independent woman who taught me about the importance of education - particularly for women and girls - first hand by returning to school in her late 30s, despite her family's discouragement. She supported me fully as I went on to study journalism and photography and  was thrilled to see me work to benefit the lives of girls and women. Ritu Saini (foreground), 21, and Rupa, 23, enjoy monsoon rains on a roof in Agra, India. Both women are acid attack survivors. A disfiguring and sometimes deadly retributive act generally taken by, or on behalf of, men whose advances the women rejected, acid attacks disfigure hundreds of women and girls in India every year. Formerly a volleyball player, Ritu was attacked by her cousin. After several reconstructive surgeries, she lost her left eye. Rupa was attacked when she was 15. Ritu now spends her days educating people about acid attacks while working at Sheroes Hangout Cafe @sheroeshangout in Agra, India, which is staffed by acid attack survivors and supported by the group @StopAcidAttacks, which advocates for policies to help acid-attack survivors.
.

It is a tremendous, if bittersweet, honor to win an award in Anja‚Äôs name. I‚Äôve long been moved by IWMF‚Äôs mission to unleash the potential of women journalists as champions of press freedom to transform the global news media. Today, I feel this is needed more than ever. I am humbled and proud that the jury would recognize my photojournalism in this way and be one of the women journalists supported and empowered by this prestigious organization. Not only will this award support my continued work, but I am grateful for the awareness such a high profile honor will bring to the stories I shared in my application, including Ritu‚Äôs above, which was made on assignment last year for @natgeo. It is a privilege to share the stories of the women and girls who truly deserve an award for their courage. #women #girls #iwmf #sheroes

At 1:23 am on April 26,¬†1986,¬†reactor # 4 at the Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant blew up. The radioactive fallout spread over thousands of square kilometers, driving more than a quarter of a million people permanently from their homes. More than 100,000 people may have succumbed to Chernobyl-related illnesses. It remains the worst nuclear accident to date.¬†More than 30 years later, the long shadow of Chernobyl continues to darken lives ‚Äî socially, environmentally, and physically.
In the 1970s, the town of Pripyat was constructed for the plant‚Äôs personnel but its 50,000 inhabitants were evacuated 36 hours after the accident.¬†Now, wind blows through the desolate¬†and chilling ghost town. In 1986, this amusement park was being readied for the annual May Day celebrations, when the reactor # 4 of the Nuclear Power Plant exploded less than 3 kilometers away.
Learn more about Chernobyl from my book and iPad App ‚ÄúThe Long Shadow of Chernobyl‚Äù ¬†@thephotosociety @natgeo @natgeocreative #Chernobyl¬†#Pripyat #Ukraine #TheLongShadowofChernobyl #nuclear #disaster #environment

31 years ago on April 26,1986 at 1:23 am, the Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant blew up after operators botched a safety test, triggering an explosion and a fire that burned for 10 days.

Recently, several European newspapers reported that one third of all wild boars hunted in countries in the path of the nuclear fallout such as the Czech Republic and Germany, still contain such high levels of radiation (Cesium-137) that their meat is not save for consumption.

During my first visit to the Chernobyl Exclusion Zone, in the early 1990‚Äôs, I photographed scientist¬†from the Department of Ecological Botany at the Swedish University in Uppsala as they worked on a study of tissue radioactivity in animals in the Chernobyl Zone. Their research concentrated on the area's wild boar and roe deer.¬† After the animals' dissection, then performed in a makeshift lab in a former kindergarten kitchen, their stomach contents were analyzed.
This image is from my ongoing project of the Chernobyl disaster and its continuing aftermath.

You can learn more about Chernobyl from my book and iPad app The Long Shadow of Chernobyl

Over the last 15 years I have made numerous trips to the Salton Sea, photographing for @natgeo, German Geo, for personal projects and I have taught private workshops there.

A victim of geography and hard-ball politics, the Salton Sea is California‚Äôs largest, most troubled lake. It lies 227 feet below sea level with no outlets and very thirsty neighbors, including a billion dollar farm economy in the bone-dry Imperial Valley, 124 golf courses in the adjacent Coachella Valley, and salt laden wetlands hosting a menagerie of wildlife in growing crisis.

With two feeder rivers and no outlet, the water level depends on evaporation, which in return increases the Salton Sea‚Äôs salinity. Now a concern is looming.

Already 25% saltier than the Pacific Ocean, the salinity in the Salton Sea is expected to further increase, potentially killing all of its life and turning it into a biologically dead sea. 
The photograph above was taken during my 2016 workshop on the Salton Sea. A quietly decaying ship rests on the shores of Bombay Beach. I‚Äôm planning to drive to the Salton Sea tomorrow in order to check on the latest developments.

In 2011, the Ukrainian government officially legalized tourism into the Exclusion Zone. Today a chilling ghost town, the city of Pripyat was originally built for the scientists and workers of the CNPP and their families. School # 3 in Pripyat, famous for its assembly of children‚Äôs gas masks spread out on the floor offers a surrealist still life in an abandoned classroom. It is one of the most popular tourist attractions. The origin of the gas masks is somewhat unclear. Some people suggest boxes of gas masks (which every school in the whole country had in storage) were originally opened by scavengers and spread out all over. 
Today, the space is rearranged by tourist providers to cater to their customers‚Äô expectations and enhance the impact of the experience.

The King of The Nakanai - In January 2016, an international caving expedition traveled to the island of New Britain in Papua New Guinea. The goal? To find and explore the areas last remaining unexplored mega-doline identified during aerial observations. On Thursday 28th January 2016, with food supplies running low, Jean-Paul Sounier sent six Papuans back to Tolel village. Only three now remained. After sharpening their machetes, they set off from camp at a determined pace with the four of us in tow. On a bearing of 270‚Äô they cut their way through the thick forest. Devastated by the cyclone in 1997, this area of the Nakanai Mountains over 1200m elevation, was hit the worst. Now a reduced canopy with increased sunlight allowing more and more different types of plants to grow on the jungle floor, including bamboo, required a herculean path-clearing effort by the three Papuans. The ground rose gradually, with occasional streambeds that needed crossing. Despite not wearing any shoes, the barefooted Papuans chose to walk straight up the steep mud slopes either side of the streambeds.  In spite of wearing the very latest hiking boots, the four of us couldn‚Äôt keep on our feet and the local Papuans found it highly amusing watching us slip and slide back down the slopes. Although Jean-Paul Sounier (pictured) used his GPS to keep on point, the Papuans seemed to have a sixth sense and took us straight to the Black Hole. 
Stay tuned for more from this fascinating story as the team try to unlock yet another secret of Papua New Guineas hidden underworld.
The expedition was sponsored by Petzl, the leading manufacturer of equipment for outdoor sport enthusiasts and professionals, whose roots were founded deep underground in the then deepest cave in the world - The Gouffre Berger. In January 2016, an international caving expedition traveled to the island of New Britain in Papua New Guinea. The goal? To find and explore the areas last remaining unexplored mega-doline identified during aerial observations. The following morning after sleeping out in the rainforest the Papuans picked the best route through the dense vegetation around the countless dolines, fallen trees and bamboo thickets and up onto the high plateau. The team made steady progress thanks to Herman‚Äôs (pictured) efficient machete work as well as his navigational skills. By mid afternoon, the team reached a point approximately an hour or so away from the estimated location of the Black Hole. At this point they began looking for a suitable place to establish base camp. For this, the site had to be close enough to Tolel to allow the porters to make the trip on foot in less than seven hours, but not too far from the Black Hole. The site had to be large enough to set up the teams big communal shelter, nine hammocks and several small huts to house almost three dozen porters and finish this construction before the late afternoon rains arrive.

In January 2016, an international caving expedition traveled to the island of New Britain in Papua New Guinea. The goal? To find and explore the area's last remaining unexplored mega-doline identified during aerial observations. It was decided to split into two teams. Four people would remain in Tolel to explore the caves familiar to the Papuans, which are located in the vicinity of the village, whilst the other four people would hike up to the plateau to look for a good site for the base camp and also locate the mysterious Black Hole. With the support of a small group of Papuans to help break trail, the team headed up into the rainforest on a reconnaissance mission, slipping and sliding on the steep wet ground. The beginning of the trail took the team down into the Wunung gorge and then up the other side. It was soon apparent that they were not going to reach their objective in one single day, so they were forced to bivi out in the forest part way up to the plateau. The Papuans took little time to construct their shelter (pictured). For the rest of us, we strung up hammocks to keep us off the jungle floor. Speaking from experience, in 2006 I once suffered a horrendous night, when I slept out on the jungle floor on the other side of the Nakanai. I got no sleep. I was eaten alive by hundreds of creepy crawlies!

In January 2016, an international caving expedition traveled to the island of New Britain in Papua New Guinea. The goal? To find and explore the areas last remaining unexplored mega-doline identified during aerial observations. The journey up into the Nakanai Mountains was relatively straightforward, especially for these four guys, who have all been to the Nakanai before. Jean-Paul Sounier (red t-shirt) has been on thirteen expeditions exploring the caves of the Nakanai. He has dedicated his entire 30-year long caving career to this tiny island, home to the largest and most wild and ferocious river caves in the world. In caving circles, he is known as ‚ÄòThe King of the Nakanai‚Äô. This is the last remaining cave feature he has not yet been to. Pictured here, the team studies maps and aerial photographs to try and pin point exactly where the mega-doline, the big black hole is and their proposed route up to it. From these maps, they learn that they will have to spend several days following a GPS point, cutting a trail through the dense jungle and camping at several points along the way. From these maps and aerial photographs they also spot other surface features along the line from the black hole to the big resurgence of water on the coast. Could there be a giant river cave in this area that has not yet been discovered‚Ä¶? Stay tuned for more from this fascinating story as the team try to unlock yet another secret of Papua New Guineas hidden underworld.

The expedition was sponsored by Petzl, the leading manufacturer of equipment for outdoor sport enthusiasts and professionals, whose roots were founded deep underground in the then deepest cave in the world - The Gouffre Berger. In the early hours of the morning on the 22nd January 2016, a small team of elite cave explorers from France, Spain and Australia embarked on a twelve-hour boat ride around the coast of East New Britain, from its capital Kokopo, to Palmalmal, in Jacquinot Bay. Led by highly experienced French explorer Jean-Paul Sounier, the team chartered two small boats carrying themselves, their caving equipment and their food supplies for four weeks away from civilisation, camped deep in the Papuan rainforest.

Their objective, to locate and explore the last remaining unexplored mega-doline of the Nakanai Mountains. A doline or sinkhole is a collapsed cave feature that breaks the surface. Typically these mega-dolines that are found in the Nakanai, such as Nare, Ora, Minye and Kavakuna, are gateways to the underground world and the only sign of what amazing caves run through this heavily forested island.
Stay tuned for more from this fascinating story as the team try to unlock yet another secret of Papua New Guineas hidden underworld.

In 1988, French cave explorer Jean-Paul Sounier took an interesting helicopter reconnaissance flight over an area of the Nakanai Mountains in East New Britain, Papua New Guinea. The pilot told him that on a previous flight he had looked down into a huge black hole, an unexplored sinkhole and one of the Nakanai‚Äôs many ‚Äòmega-dolines‚Äô. Later during the flight they discovered a large volume of water resurging from a cave along the coast. Could this be the downstream end of the mysterious black hole the pilot had spotted during his flight? The following years were spent exploring other objectives that this vast karst landscape contains, Muruk, Ora, Mageni, and Wowo. The mysterious ghost river slowly faded from his memory‚Ä¶ until, the summer of 2014, and after an expedition to another karst area in New Britain, he began looking for a worthy objective to take him back to the Nakanai Mountains. After studying aerial photos he noticed, on a plateau along the left bank of Wunung Gorge, a black and white mark indicating a surface sinkhole. Could this be the very chasm that the helicopter pilot from 1988 spotted? Venturing to a plateau that has never been explored and mapping its underground passageways, what an enticing proposition! 
Over the next week I will publish a photograph a day telling this fascinating story of the teams journey to explore the last remaining mega-doline of the Nakanai Mountains and their quest to unlock yet another secret of Papua New Guineas hidden underworld.

The expedition was sponsored by Petzl, the leading manufacturer of equipment for outdoor sport enthusiasts and professionals, whose roots were founded deep underground in the then deepest cave in the world - The Gouffre Berger. Following a very long day underground, the team re-emerge from the cave having achieved all their scientific and mapping objectives. The Abyss of Cenote (cave) in the Italian Dolomites is mainly one large chamber (pictured here) with a narrow shaft that enters from the top containing a 165m deep ice plug. The ‚Äòtongue' of the ice plug can be seen in the top of this picture with a striking black and white appearance in which the folds can clearly be seen.  At the bottom of the cave, 285m below the surface, the floor is covered in a slope of breakdown blocks that have fallen from the roof and walls. These rocks cover another large mass of ice, the thickness of which is unknown. The laser scan of this lower part of the cave was carried out in November 2015 and tied into the scans of the upper part of the cave, which were taken in October/November 2016. The La Venta exploration team will return to this cave in a few years time to repeat the scan and monitor at high resolution the changes in the ice plug and ice floor.

The Abyss of Cenote (cave) at nearly 3,000m in the Italian Dolomites is a unique cave 285 m deep with a large ice plug in its entrance. The ice plug extends down the first 165 m, finishing in a large ‚Äòtongue‚Äô seen here on the right. Up until this point, the route through the cave is down the side and through the middle of the ice plug. At this point when the ice plug finishes, the cave turns into a normal limestone shaft down which one must rappel, mostly free-hanging (i.e., away from the wall in empty space), in a constant shower of water from the melting ice up way above. Pictured here, the scanning team are making their way slowly but surely down the ice tongue, and into the huge void below. It gets more and more epic with every step that's taken. Each step with the crampons cuts into the ice and sends tiny shards of glass-like pieces falling into the blackness below. Tommaso Santagata (left) of the La Venta Exploration team and Farouk Kadded (right) of Leica Geosystems, France, have set up one of Leica‚Äôs state-of-the-art 3D laser scanning devices. They have secured it partly to the ice and partly to the rock behind from which they can scan in nearly all directions. From my lofty position a few feet above them, I watched every movement hoping they didn‚Äôt drop anything. This team is at the forefront of 3D laser scanning in caves, they‚Äôre using really cutting edge stuff in very complex and technically challenging environments to map caves.

Deep underground and inside the giant ice plug that sits wedged in the upper part of the Abyss of Cenote (cave) like a cork in a bottle, Professor Christoph Sp√∂tl from the Innsbruck University Quaternary Research Group and Andreas Treyer scrape the dirty layer away from the surface of the ice before drilling samples of clean ice for stable isotopes and pollen analysis. Only recently has this cave been open to scientists like Christoph to take such important samples. For many decades a lake was present in the depression at the entrance. Then in 1994 some divers hiked up the mountain to take a closer look at the lake only to find that it had disappeared! Subsequent investigation revealed a giant cave 285m deep with a large ice plug in the entrance, that for many years had prevented the wonders that lie beneath from being discovered.

The Abyss of Cenote (cave) in the heart of the Italian Dolomites is predominately a vertical cave with very few areas of flat ground to stand up on. To get around in such a cave, cavers typically use SRT (single rope technique), which involves abseiling (descending) or prussiking (ascending), down and up one rope. All members of this expedition were very competent at SRT and enjoyed swinging around on the ropes suspended hundreds of feet above the ground. Pictured here, GEO magazine writer Lars Abromeit reaches the top of one of many rope pitches, which is anchored to the rock, though in other parts of the cave ice screws had to be used instead. At nearly 3000m elevation, the first signs of being at altitude start to affect some people, and climbing up 285 m up ropes from the bottom of the cave can be quite tiring. Thankfully it is possible to relax and just back in the harness if a break is needed, which is especially a good thing when doing this wearing crampons. #AbyssOfCenote

One of the main objectives of the Abyss of Cenote expedition was to produce a highly precise laser scan survey of the cave. Here, Farouk Kadded (left) of Leica Geosystems, France, and Tommaso Santagata (right) of the La Venta Exploration team are working in the ‚Äòwind tunnel‚Äô in the centre of the ice plug. Up until this point, the route through the cave is largely vertical, on ropes, between the cave wall and the outside of the ice plug. Here, the route turns horizontal for a short distance before resuming its vertical nature. Due to the change in size of the passage here as compared to the much larger chamber at the bottom of the cave, a strong wind blows through this tunnel, which changes direction depending on the temperature at the surface. Combining the already cold temperature of the cave with the strong wind makes working in this part of the cave rather challenging, especially when sat around for extended periods of time working the laser scanner.

Just inside the entrance of Abyss of Cenote (cave), Professor Christoph Sp√∂tl from the Innsbruck University Quaternary Research Group is seen here checking a data logger for environmental monitoring of the cave's meteorology. Assisted by Dr. Gina Moseley (@negreenland_caves) and Andreas Treyer (background), the researchers also replaced pollen traps at different locations and elevations throughout the cave. Unfortunately, after a long rigging trip to the bottom of the cave, it was discovered that one of the loggers had been washed away in floods during the previous year. Still, they were able to collect some useful information from the loggers and traps in order to better understand the flux of airflow (and pollen) through the cave. #AbyssOfCenote

When on an expedition I often like to break up the photography by drawing sketches in my diary. To get away from the battery charging, the digital screens, and get back to the basics of a pen(cil) and paper is really therapeutic, and it reminds me of where I first found my love of art. On The Abyss of Cenote expedition, I made this drawing of the iconic entrance of the cave, the place where the Lake of Two Forks once stood before it drained into the underworld. Here, two cavers are walking up to the entrance with the backdrop of the Dolomites in the distance, whilst another two cavers are already in the sinkhole, working their way along the traverse line, past the top of the ice plug, and into the cave.
